My recent videos focus on the serious public health threats affecting communities in Soweto slum, Jinja. Through these recordings, I wanted to highlight the daily realities that many residents face, especially challenges related to poor sanitation, waste management, and limited access to clean water.

In the videos, you can see open drainage systems filled with stagnant water, which create breeding grounds for mosquitoes and increase the risk of diseases like malaria. Poor waste disposal is also a major issue, with garbage often left uncollected, contributing to the spread of infections and environmental pollution.

Another key issue I captured is overcrowding. Many families live in small spaces with limited ventilation, which increases the risk of communicable diseases. Children are especially vulnerable due to exposure to unsafe environments and limited access to proper healthcare and hygiene facilities.

The purpose of these videos is not just to show the problem, but to raise awareness and encourage action. Communities, leaders, and organizations need to work together to improve sanitation, promote health education, and invest in better infrastructure.

These videos are a call to action—to remind us that public health is a shared responsibility, and even small changes can make a big difference in improving lives in areas like Soweto, Jinja.
